likely talking about Miles Davis\u2019s \u201cKind of Blue,\u201d Elvis\nPresley\u2019s self-titled album, and Frank Sinatra\u2019s \u201cIn the Wee Small Hours,\u201d\namong a few others.\n\nIs it possible in 100 years that some obscure album from the 1950s will\nsuddenly be hailed as the decade\u2019s masterpiece? Yes. But it\u2019s not likely. Some\nlevel of consensus does seem to appear over time, despite all of the\nunexpected non-musical factors that influence list construction.\n\n### Methods\n\nThis project began with a Google sheet created by Chris Eckert, Rolling\nStone's 500 Greatest Albums 2003 v 2012 v. 2020.\n\nThis dataset is actually misleading, because the 2003 ranking seems to come\nfrom a book published by Rolling Stone, where the editor chose to change the\noriginal ranking: \"For the book version of the RS 500 I have eliminated a few\ncompilation albums that simply repeated material appearing elsewhere on albums\nthat made the list. I've also combined the two volumes of Robert Johnson's\n\u2018King of the Delta Blues Singers\u2019 into the more readily available \u2018Complete\nRecordings.\u2019 That left room for eight new albums to bubble up from the bottom\nof our tally.\"\n\nFor this project, we decided to use Rolling Stone\u2019s original ranking, which\nyou can find on the Internet Archive here. (We also acquired the original\nprint magazine issue, published in 2003). The 2003 judges come from the\nmagazine and book. 2020 judges are available here).\n\nYou can access our full dataset here.\n\nThe Pudding is a digital publication that explains ideas debated in culture\nwith visual essays.\n\n  * ABOUT\n  * FACEBOOK\n  * TWITTER\n  * INSTAGRAM\n  * PATREON\n  * PRIVACY\n  * NEWSLETTER\n  * RSS\n\n", "frontpage": false}
